{"id":"2003.06901","submitter":"Cyril Cayron","authors":"Cyril Cayron","title":"Solving constrained optimization problems without Lagrange multipliers","comments":"18 pages, 10 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.OC cond-mat.mtrl-sci","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Constrained optimization problems exist in many domains of science, such as\nthermodynamics, mechanics, economics, etc. These problems are classically\nsolved with the help of the Lagrange multipliers and the Lagrangian function.\nHowever, the disadvantage of this approach is that it artificially increases\nthe dimensionality of the problem. Here, we show that the determinant of the\nJacobian of the problem (function to optimize and constraints) is null. This\nextra equation transforms any equality-constrained optimization problem into a\nsolving problem of same dimension. We also introduced the constraint matrices\nas the largest square submatrices of the Jacobian of the constraints. The\nboundaries of the constraint domain are given by the nullity of their\ndeterminants. The constraint matrices also permit to write the function to be\noptimized as a Taylor series of any of its variable, with its coefficients\nalgebraically determined by an iterative process of partial derivation.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 15 Mar 2020 19:35:36 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 5 May 2020 17:48:28 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Sun, 10 Jan 2021 18:23:02 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-01-12"}
